text: This movie just feeds into a pre-existing problem: Too many of our youth have a limited (and unrealistic) understanding of what "success" means. It's great to have "ambition", but ambition requires EDUCATION and HARD WORK to be realized. It would also, ideally,  be tempered with INTEGRITY. All things being equal, it's better to be rich than poor, but being "Floyd Mayweather rich", isn't necessarily the pinnacle of "success." There are so many components to "HAPPINESS", and money is just one of them. This is all common sense, but I know that there many kids NOT having these lessons taught, or these values instilled in them.

text: Ron O'Neal, the original Priest, was cool, but the new Superfly looks even better with more action, very gorgeous photography and a strong anti-drug emphasis that only began with the version from 72. Trevor Jackson could make his Super Fly rock, like Samuel Jackson (relation?) did with the 2001 remake of Shaft. I'm seeing it first time tonight on Amazon Prime so wish me well.  Imagine what remakes of Truck Turner, Cleopatra Jones or Trouble Man could do for the black and the white community!!! Last time, blaxploitation films tore us up. Today it could bring us together, in the movies or at home. Unified. The way it was meant to be!!!
